<br>
The wagon moved ever on for what seemed like days.  Coming in and out of consciousness Draehan was only half aware of what fate lay at the end of the road. He could only open his eyes for moment before the pounding on his head forced him to retreat into darkness once more. <br>
<br>
“Ahh, here we are!” Groganthanos spoke to himself.<br>
<br>
He pulls the wagon over by the gates of a small stone arena. He jumped from the wagon and lumbered to the back to unload. <br>
<br>
“I’m back! come put this junk away.” He boomed.<br>
<br>
Shortly after 3 Ogre boys trotted out from what looked to be a storage room. The oldest nodded to his father wile the other 2 started picking bags and weapons by what they could carry. Garganthanos lifted the limp Tier’Dal man from the cart by his belt, only needing one hand for the effort.<br>
<br>
“Here take him to the back and see that he’s awake for the fight.” Graganthanos growled, as he tossed the lifeless man at his son.<br>
<br>
“Okeys dad, meas do dat.” <br>
 <br>
                            *                                      *                           * <br>
<br>
Draehan woke with a start as the cold water hit his face, it stung like needles. It took him only seconds to focus, his eyes darting around the cell instinctively looking for an escape. The small jail was only a stone room with bars for a door, blood dirt and urine covered the floor. Draehan stood groggily, the smell of the floor driving him to his feet. He staggered, his wits slowly returning to him. Walking to the gates he could see he was not alone, countless other cells lined the walls, filled with all manner of beats. He shook the bars, testing there strength before giving up completely, he would have to wait for what ever was in store for him.<br>
<br>
Hours passed with nothing, no hint of what fate lay before him. The young man jumped as he heard the faint clank of armor growing closer.<br>
<br>
“You ready to fight boy?” The familiar boom of Groganthanos’s voice shattered the silence.<br>
<br>
He walked to the gates, unlocking and tossing them open. With out a word he grabbed Draehan by the wrist, wrenching him down the hall to a new room. Warriors and fighters of all race and creed lined the walls of the packed room. Sounds of metal clashing with metal as the armored figures shifted and moved was deafening.<br>
<br>
Groganthanos walked to the center of the room and put a massive hand to his mouth “Alright listen up. Tonight’s event is a free for all. Ya fight till ya die, and if ya don’t die ya win the pot, got that?” <br>
<br>
The room grew quiet for a moment before erupting into a roar of cheers and yells. A chant of  “glory for the warlord!” broke out from a small band of Ogres in a back corner.<br>
 <br>
Groganthanos shot a hand up into the air, calling for silence. “The fight starts in a moment, everyone to the arena floor and find your positions.”<br>
<br>
With astonishing obedience the room cleared out, moving in 2 lines to the arena floor where the battle would begin. Draenhan stood dumfounded in the center of the now empting room. This was how he was going to die? His mind raced, he had no weapons, no armor, and no skill in battle. With a fierce shove from his captor he was forced ever closer to the arena floor that spelled his death.<br>
<br>
He stood in the stand of the open arena, his back pressed to one of the walls as he eyed the other fighters closely. His thoughts were not on winning, only on living through the night. There were 10 or so other combatants, all grunting and cheering, convincing them selves of there own bravery. There had to be a way to live through this his mind chanted. The mage scanned the arena, looking for weak spots in armor, flaws in there stance, anything that would give him even a glimmer of a chance. With in seconds a trumpet sounded, he was out of time. <br>
<br>
The roar of battle filled the circular death trap, weapons clashing, screams of pain and anger. He turned just in time to see the mace swing at his face, he was not strong but he was fast. With a quick motion of his head the mace smashed into the stone wall behind him. The mace was in the air once more, enough to crack the skull of an Ogre no less a Tier’Dal, but it never finished its descent. From the right a human’s sword plunged into the troll’s side, just under his arm, causing the troll to whirl around in pain. The human grinned, knowing the wound would cut off the use of the arm that used the mace. Draehan did not stay long enough to see the swing that caused the trolls cry to be cut short, he had to keep moving, to stay out of reach of the others. <br>
<br>
The battle raged on, one by one the fighters fell, blood slowly painting the sand red. There could only be about 5 left, only 5 more to avoid, and if he survived, one would need to die by his hand. He leapt over the body of a barbarian, just avoiding the sword thrust at his head. Only minutes now, just a little longer. His thoughts were cut short as the shield slammed into his chest, tossing the small framed Tier’Dal a good 3 feet. He gasped for air; the shield had caught him off guard and forced the air from his lungs. Draehan looked around desperately, the pain in his chest making it hard to move. It was then he realized how much he looked like the bodies that lay near him, his red robes soaked in the blood as he lay on the ground. This was the answer; this is how he would survive, unmoving, and patient in the sand. The others would not try to kill one who was already dead.<br>
<br>
<br>
The battle lasted for what seemed like hours until all was quiet, one lone troll stood over the body of the last to fall, a human that had put up a good fight. Draehan risked opening only one of his eyes, he needed a weapon. The troll looked around the arena once, his dim mind not catching the faint raise and fall of Draehan's chest. <br>
<br>
“Rahhhhhh! “ The troll’s voice cried out in victory as he turned to face a platform where Groganthanos stood silent. <br>
<br>
The veteran warriors keen eyes could see what the troll could not, the slight movement of the red robes in the center of the area. The troll was quiet a moment, his mind working to understand why he was not being rewarded. Draehan worked quickly, grabbing the shaft of an arrow from the quiver of a near by corpse, the only weapon in reach light enough for the small man to wield. He crept ever closer to the troll, he would not die today... He could not die today.  The lone warrior turned with only enough time to see the crazed mage leap at him with shear desperation, all of his weight forced behind the attack. The troll raised his weapon but it was to late, the arrow head lodged into his eye, forcing its way into his skull. He wailed in pain as his scenes started to dull, the fatal blow numbing his mind. Draehan did not let go, anger and adrenalin welling up inside of him; he pushed on the shaft of the arrow with all of his might, driving it to hit the back of the trolls skull. <br>
<br>
A faint clapping was the only sound that broke the crazed Tier’Dal's attention from the troll that lay at his feet. As he looked up Groganthanos saluted him with a quick thrust to his breastplate. <br>
<br>
“Well done boy. I didn’t expect this outcome at all.” With a quick motion of his hand the eldest son appeared at his side. “Go see that this man is cleaned up and bring him to my office” <br>
<br>
With that said he turned to leave his boys to finish up the work, remove the bodies from the arena and fetch the winner of the battle...<br>
